item_text: She/he performs the clinical examinations according to standardized methods.
The student provides accurate and authoritative information by taking a careful and complete history.
Uses appropriate communication skills while taking a history, performing a clinical examination, or teaching the patient or family.

She/he patiently, timely, and correctly performs the care and treatment procedure (such as nasogastric tube (NG tube, urinary catheterization, arterial blood gas (ABG), Insertion of a Peripheral Intravenous Cannula, blood collection, etc.).
She/he knows the correct use of the medical equipment and the necessity of regular maintenance of the equipment and checks for safety.
She/he is well aware of the patient's situation (assessment, diagnosis, and treatment plan).
Deliver accurate, high-quality, and compassionate patient education in a way that is understandable by the patients and their family members.
She/he has adequate knowledge of how to diagnose and treat common disorders in clinical placements.
Treat each patient as a unique being and have respect for the patient's individuality.
Treat the patients and their companions with dignity and respect.
Respect the patient's beliefs, culture, customs, and practice.
In case of going on leave of absence or being absent, the student makes the necessary arrangement.
Respect patient privacy.
Follow the rules and regulations of the department and hospital.
The student maintains a professional appearance and dress code in accordance with the policy of the clinical setting.
Wear the identification badge in a visible position at all times during working hours in the hospital.
Treat professors, seniors, and people with more experience with respect and dignity.
The students' caring attention is accomplished by applying maximum efforts to respond to the patient's needs and requests as quickly as possible.
Perform her/his duties responsibly and to the highest safety standards.
Demonstrate professional courtesy and respect when communicating with professors, colleagues, patients, etc.
He/she is always punctual and shows up to work on time.
Demonstrates responsibility and accountability for the care provided.
She/he is open to criticism.

In discussion with a colleague, she/he shows a great capacity to accept logical reasoning and strive to maintain a respectful and constructive atmosphere in the discussion (avoid aggressiveness, destructive, and baseless criticism).
She/he avoids all confrontation, both verbal and physical.
She/he seeks to receive feedback on her performance and accepts it when it is given.
she/he is always calm and composed in difficult situations. She/he keeps cool and can solve problems quickly and efficiently.
At clinical placement, all diagnostic measures and treatments are performed under the full supervision of qualified professionals.
She/he knows her/his scientific limitations and asks for advice and help if necessary.
To get scientifically prepared, she/he studies relevant subjects to a sufficient extent.
Report suspicions of impairment or incompetence concerning their colleagues to tackle professional misconduct.
Follows up on the outcomes of all patients cared for and ensures the provision of the necessary information for patients continued after the discharge.
She/he actively participate in presentation of academic conferences and group discussions.
The student pay attention to patients as an individual and is concern for the physical, psychological, and social aspects of their disease.
As a team member, the student respects his/her colleagues communicates with them effectively, and provides invaluable feedback as needed.
The student has the ability to recognize and value the role of others.
Respect the patient's right charter under different conditions and ensure that the patient's rights are not violated.
All cases of patient admission, hospitalization, or difficulties in the treatment process are reported to the trainer, Nurses/or hospital ward staff.
The student does not judge or prejudice.
The student provides constructive verbal and written feedback to other members of the healthcare team.
If the student notices a medical error from a colleague, approach the colleague and gently bring up the situation in a non-judgmental way to take immediate corrective or preventive measures.
The student ensures that the patient's best interest is considered at the center of medical decisions, regardless of the student's personal opinion.
Maintain patient confidentiality.
The student actively seeks advice, assistance, or direction from professors, teachers, and other students in order to keep up-to-date with current knowledge and skills.
To provide an integrated and dynamic treatment plan for the patient, the student worked in collaboration with other members of the healthcare providers as needed.
The student spends enough time in all stages of the patient care process.
The students provide a complete and accurate record of the patient's condition and the medical care given to the patient.
The student has a fair and supportive behavior when interacting with patients and other healthcare professionals.
The student has the ability to manage time effectively and set priorities for patient care.
The student can advocate for their patient's needs and has a reasonably high regard for each patient's wishes.
The student is a great team member. He/she respects the position of others and works constructively and positively in the group.
The student observes justice in dealing with different patients regardless of race, religion, opinion, gender, etc.

In the presence of patients and companions, she/he does not criticize the colleagues decisions, and follow-up interventions are anticipated only at the patient's request or due to clinical doubt (without judging the performance of her/his colleague).

In the event of a medical error, while accepting the responsibility, she/he takes immediate corrective measures by informing the patient's doctor/professor of the mistake so that the action can be made as soon as possible.
If she/he is not competent enough to meet the patient's needs and provide care with high quality, ask for help from the professors or peers and inform the patient about it.
